included.description:
To satisfy UMass' honors graduation requirement and practice high-level political science research, I completed a thesis honors seminar led by Professor Robert Paul Musgrave. The seminar was designed to help each student write an individual thesis paper based on our own research. My research concerned Trinidad & Tobago and how its growth and development relate to the larger literature on oil and natural gas dependency. I have included the abstract below:

ABSTRACT:
Many political scientists argue that economic dependency on oil and natural gas makes a country more susceptible to slow growth and authoritarianism. But Trinidad & Tobago seems to contradict this theory. After attaining significant wealth through oil exports in the 1970s and natural gas wealth in the last twenty years, Trinidad & Tobago is one of the wealthiest and most democratic countries in the Americas. Through this research, I argue that â while Trinidad & Tobago has not yet sufficiently diversified its economy away inherently finite fossil fuels â the overall impact of these natural resources on the nationâs government, economy, and quality of life has been positive. While historically rich and liberal countries like Norway have avoided this âresource curseâ before, Trinidad & Tobago only gained independence in the 60s and was relatively poor before the oil shocks of the 70s. Proving that T&T is not a victim of this apparent curse casts significant doubt upon the âresource pessimismâ school of thought. Support for this claim â that the success of natural resource-reliant states is conditional on institutional efficacy â comes from statistical evidence that Trinidad & Tobagoâs economy and democracy have consistently performed better than average for a country with this level of natural resource dependency. Also, increases in oil and natural gas wealth in Trinidad & Tobago have coincided with significant economic progress and improvements to the countryâs government and social welfare over time.
included.title: Honors Thesis -- Is Trinidad & Tobago a Victim of "The Resource Curse"?
